"Irnham, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1425–1476":"about 1425–1476","1425–1476":"1425–1476","1428–1470":"1428–1470","1451–1522":"1451–1522","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","about 1470":"about 1470","1425":"1425","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","1530":"1530","about 1425":"about 1425","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1428":"1428","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Edlington, Lincolnshire, England":"Edlington, Lincolnshire, England","Irnham, Lincolnshire, England":"Irnham, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thimbleby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name, primarily from Thimbleby (Lincs), but also from Thimbleby (NR Yorks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Thimblebee","meanings":["English:  see  Thimbleby  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":30,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Robert Thimbleby was born about 1425, in Edlington, Lincolnshire, England as the son of Thomas Thimbley. He married Margaret Bilesby in 1450, in Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1476, in Irnham, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1425–1476":"umbes 1425–1476","1425–1476":"1425–1476","1428–1470":"1428–1470","1451–1522":"1451–1522","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","about 1470":"umbes 1470","1425":"1425","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","1530":"1530","about 1425":"umbes 1425","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1428":"1428","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Edlington, Lincolnshire, England":"Edlington, Lincolnshire, England","Irnham, Lincolnshire, England":"Irnham, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1425–1476":"noin 1425–1476","1425–1476":"1425–1476","1428–1470":"1428–1470","1451–1522":"1451–1522","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1400